\nUEFA Champions League<br />\r\nTuesday 14 September 2021<br />\r\nKick-off 8pm</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Important Information</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>All supporters attending our home games this season will need to provide evidence they are at low risk of transmitting Covid-19 to enter Stamford Bridge and Kingsmeadow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supporters will need to provide proof of full Covid-19 vaccination (with both doses received at least 14 days prior to the match) or proof of a negative Lateral Flow Test (LFT - from age 11 and over) carried out within 48 hours of the fixture kicking off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Proof of full vaccination should be supplied via your NHS Covid Pass on the NHS app, or a vaccination letter. Supporters displaying a negative Lateral Flow result should do so on the NHS app, or via a text message or email from NHS Test and Trace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stewards will check your Covid-19 status at your point of entry. If you are using your phone, please ensure it has sufficient battery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Ticket sales information</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please note: Due to shortness of time, there will be no movers&rsquo; day for displaced season ticket holders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Friday 3 September from 2pm until Monday 6 September at 5pm:</strong>&nbsp;Season ticket holders can purchase their own seat. Displaced season ticket holders will be able to purchase tickets not held in reservation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tuesday 7 September from 10am:</strong>&nbsp;Tickets will be sold to members at one ticket per person.&nbsp;Season ticket holders who do not already have a ticket will be able to purchase at one ticket per person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Wednesday 8 September from 10am:</strong>&nbsp;Season ticket holders and members can purchase an extra two tickets (maximum of three in total).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Wednesday 8 September from 2pm:</strong>&nbsp;Tickets will go on general sale maximum four tickets per person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Non-disabled supporters can apply online or through telephone sales at the relevant on sales period detailed above.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Displaced seats</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Matthew Harding Lower:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Row A/Seats 57 -96 Row B/Seats 57 -73 Row C/Seats 57-73</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shed Lower:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Row 1/Seats 119-138 Row 2/Seats 123-138 Row 3/Seats 123-138</p>\r\n\r\n<p>East Lower:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Row H/Seats 97-110 Row J/Seats 97-110 Row K/Seats 97-110 Row L/Seats 97-110</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Row P/Seats 55-82 Row R/Seats 55-82 Row U/Seats 111-138 Row T/Seats 111-38</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Disabled Members Application Process</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Disabled supporters can apply by telephone sale on the disability line 0371 811 2012 or international 0044 207 915 1950 or by submitting the application form to access@chelseafc.com during the relevant sales period as detailed above.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supporters who are registered disabled wishing to apply by email can download the home disabled ticket application form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To receive a personal assistant ticket disabled members will need to apply by telephone sale or via the application form and not purchasing online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All ticket sales are subject to availability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Accessible Car Parking</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supporters with a valid blue badge can apply for a car parking space from 10am on Thursday 9 September. Car parking spaces are subject to availability and can be applied for by emailing access@chelseafc.com</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Dispatching of tickets</u><br />\r\nSupporters will need to ensure they have a valid email address registered in their online account as all tickets are print@home and will be dispatched via email immediately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supporters should print the tickets off in advance of matchday as there is no facility at Stamford Bridge to print them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Duplicate tickets</u><br />\r\nDuplicate tickets will only be given to the individual season ticket holder or member.<br />\r\nSupporters should visit the ticket office on the day of the match with photo ID and where applicable the season ticket/membership card.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Loyalty points</u><br />\r\nSupporters will receive 5 (five) loyalty points for this match.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Ticket exchange</u><br />\r\nThere will be no ticket exchange in operation for this fixture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A &pound;2.00 administration fee will be added to each transaction</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Match dates and ticket on-sale dates are subject to change. Please check the website for the latest information.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Please note: The home fixtures against Malmo and Juventus will be sold in due course to season ticket holders and members.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Chelsea Women v Brighton - Sat 2 Oct - 11.30am</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tickets will go on general sale at 10am on Monday 6 September.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Chelsea v Arsenal PL2 (Stamford Bridge) - Sun 19 Sep - 12pm</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tickets are now on general sale.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Chelsea v Liverpool PL2 (Kingsmeadow) - Fri 24 Sep - 7pm&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nTickets will go on general sale at 10am on Monday 6 September.</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 04:26:38','2021-09-04 04:26:38'),(13,'1630753251dXv1ou.jpeg','1630753251q6Aj77.jpeg',3,'IMPORTANT INFORMATION ON CHAMPIONS LEAGUE TRAVEL','Supporters planning to attend our upcoming Champions League away fixtures are strongly urged to refrain from making any travel arrangements until more information is available.','<h3>Supporters planning to attend our upcoming Champions League away fixtures are strongly urged to refrain from making any travel arrangements until more information is available.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The draw for this season&rsquo;s UEFA Champions League group stage takes place at 5pm (UK time) today and many fans will be eagerly awaiting the news of our first three away trips in the competition, as we open our defence of the European crown we claimed in Porto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, with many of the vital details surrounding those potential away trips still to be determined, even after our opponents are decided, supporters are advised to wait for further information before booking travel to those games.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although we will find out which teams we will be facing in the group stage this evening, the precise schedule and dates for all of those fixtures, home and away, will not be known until Saturday at the latest. In addition, rules on international travel between the UK and other countries continue to be subject to change and are constantly under review by respective governments, due to the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the same reason, UEFA are also yet to confirm the availability of tickets for away fans at Champions League games. Neutral venues, closed stadiums and the absence of away fans are all still possibilities, as has been the case during the qualifying stages of this season&rsquo;s European competitions and will be again for matches during September&rsquo;s international break. A decision regarding away club ticketing is currently under review and further information from UEFA is expected shortly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the relevant information regarding tickets and travel for our Champions League group games will be communicated to supporters on the official Chelsea website, The 5th Stand app and our social media channels as soon as it becomes available.</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 04:30:51','2021-09-04 04:30:51'),(14,'16307535100mTsu5.jpeg','1630753510QO0yP0.jpeg',3,'INTERNATIONALS: BABA HELPS GHANA TO VICTORY AND YOUNGSTER SCORES','INTERNATIONALS: BABA HELPS GHANA TO VICTORY AND YOUNGSTER SCORES','<h3><strong>Baba Rahman was the only Chelsea player involved in a senior men&rsquo;s international today as Ghana&rsquo;s World Cup qualifying campaign got off to a good start, but there was plenty of action for young Blues including an England goalscorer.</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Baba played the full game at left-back for the Black Stars as they defeated Ethiopia 1-0 in Cape Coast. Mubarak Wakaso netted the only goal with a superb long-range strike on 35 minutes, and although Ghana were far from their best they got the job done to earn the three points. They will likely have a trickier assignment in South Africa on Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Qualification for the 2023 European Under-21 Championship started badly for a couple of Blues tonight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thierno Ballo came on with an hour played in Austria Under-21&rsquo;s 3-1 loss in Norway. The midfielder, now on loan at Rapid Vienna, had two shots saved as Austria chased an equaliser before the Norwegians finished the game late on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sam McClelland played the first half of Northern Ireland Under-21&rsquo;s 4-1 loss in Malta, with the defender withdrawn during the interval with his side having already conceded three goals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>England Under-21&rsquo;s friendly against Romania, scheduled to take place today, was called off because of two positive Covid-19 tests in the Three Lions camp. They are due to host Kosovo at Turf Moor on Tuesday in their first qualifier, with Conor Gallagher and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/on-loan-players/levi-colwill\">Levi Colwill</a>&nbsp;the Chelsea players in that squad.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/08/15/U18s-vs-West-Brom-Castledine\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:66.6176%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/VwwhlTy\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Newport, England Under-18s drew 1-1 with their Welsh counterparts. Brodi Hughes was brought on at half-time, with Lewis Hall introduced shortly before the hour as England sought an equaliser which eventually arrived with 15 minutes remaining.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At Under-17 level, England beat Romania 2-0 in the Syrenka Cup with captain Leo Castledine opening the scoring. Sam Rak-Sakyi and Billy Gee also started, with Ronnie Stutter on the bench.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 04:35:10','2021-09-04 04:35:10'),(15,'1630760343EzlDk7.jpeg','16307603438f3zzP.jpeg',2,'JORGINHO ON COBHAM BRAGGING RIGHTS AND ITALY’S NEXT CHALLENGE','JORGINHO ON COBHAM BRAGGING RIGHTS AND ITALY’S NEXT CHALLENGE','<h2><strong>Jorginho&rsquo;s focus tonight returns to international football as Italy host Bulgaria in a World Cup qualifier, and our midfielder has been assessing how the Azzurri can build on their triumph at Euro 2020.</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Italy won their first international tournament since 2006 with a penalty shoot-out victory over England at Wembley. It crowned a fantastic couple of months for&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/jorginho?pageTab=biography\">Jorginho</a>, who was instrumental in both Chelsea&rsquo;s Champions League triumph and his adopted country&rsquo;s continental pan-European success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It all meant when he reported back to Cobham in early August, it was he who had the bragging rights over his club team-mates&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/mason-mount?pageTab=biography\">Mason Mount</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/reece-james?pageTab=biography\">Reece James</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/ben-chilwell?pageTab=biography\">Ben Chilwell</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;I&#39;ve enjoyed it loads, they didn&#39;t enjoy it much!&rsquo; laughed Jorginho when asked about it this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;I have to say they welcomed me back, but thank goodness we won... I enjoyed that little period.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2021/08/26/jorginho-named-uefa-men-s-player-of-the-year-\">Jorginho named UEFA Men&#39;s Player of the Year</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2021/09/01/internationals--christensen-and-mendy-taste-victory\">Last night&#39;s international round-up</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2021/08/30/big-chelsea-effort-pleases-jorginho-at-anfield\">Jorginho assesses Chelsea&#39;s most recent game</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/07/27/Mount_Jorginho_GettyImages-1328208937\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:62.7941%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/BxXQ10t\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:29:03','2021-09-04 06:29:03'),(16,'1630760612VHRG2u.jpeg','16307606127yvyk9.jpeg',2,'TANYA OXTOBY JOINS CHELSEA WOMEN AS ASSISTANT COACH','TANYA OXTOBY JOINS CHELSEA WOMEN AS ASSISTANT COACH','<h2><strong>Chelsea FC Women is delighted to announce the appointment of Tanya Oxtoby as assistant coach. She moves to Chelsea following a three-and-a-half-year spell at Bristol City Women.</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oxtoby joins&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/managers/emma-hayes\">Emma Hayes</a>&nbsp;and her backroom staff just in time for the start of the 2021/22 season, which begins this Sunday 5 September against Arsenal at the Emirates Stadium.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;To be joining such an illustrious team of players and staff is a true honour,&#39; said Oxtoby.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;I always said it would take something special for me to end my maternity leave early, and when this opportunity arose, and after to speaking to Emma and Paul, it felt like the ideal move for me. I&rsquo;m looking forward to working not only with world-class players, but the amazingly talented staff at the club and being able to contribute to further success.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A qualified sports psychologist, the Australian is also a UEFA A-Licence coach and comes with a wealth of experience, featuring on the pitch for a number of Australian clubs, most notably at Perth Glory in the W-League. Oxtoby went on to join Chelsea Women&rsquo;s general manager&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/managers/paul-green\">Paul Green</a>&nbsp;at Doncaster Rovers Belles in 2012, where she played against Chelsea in Hayes&rsquo; first-ever game in charge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The defender transitioned into coaching with Notts County Ladies, ahead of joining Birmingham City Ladies as assistant coach in 2017 before her most recent appointment as team manager at Bristol City Women.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fill,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,g_auto,h_382,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/women%27s-team/GettyImages-1284128421\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:56.1765%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/GB887Gm\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chelsea Women general manager Paul Green added: &lsquo;We are pleased to add Tanya to our coaching team. She is a coach with considerable experience in the WSL and a good track record of developing players.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;We feel that she will add another dimension to our talented group, both on and off the pitch, that will impact the team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;We look forward to having Tanya join us.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Welcome to Chelsea, Tanya!</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:33:32','2021-09-04 06:33:32'),(17,'1630760837HyOoYa.jpeg','1630760837vymQAD.jpeg',2,'SIMON GREENBERG','It is with immense sadness that Chelsea Football Club learned of the passing of our former director Simon Greenberg at the age of only 52.','<h2><strong>It is with immense sadness that Chelsea Football Club learned of the passing of our former director Simon Greenberg at the age of only 52.</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Simon was appointed the club&rsquo;s director of communications in 2004, the first person to undertake that new full-time position at Chelsea. It was the early stages of Roman Abramovich&rsquo;s ownership and Chelsea was rapidly modernising and expanding into a globally renowned football power, and Simon played an important part in that, advising the club&rsquo;s owner and Board on policy and strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chelsea Chairman Bruce Buck said: &lsquo;We were deeply saddened to hear of Simon&rsquo;s illness, and then devastated to learn of his passing. Simon&rsquo;s time at the club covered a period of incredible growth and new success, and he thrived under the pressure the media attention provided. Simon played a vitally important role and helped carry the club through those hectic times with enthusiasm and wit, just two of his many impressive characteristics that made him such a pleasure to work with and be around.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;We hope the shared memories his family and friends have of Simon help them through this difficult period and the time ahead. We will always remember Simon very fondly here at Chelsea Football Club.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On moving from Fleet Street, where he had held top jobs in sports journalism, Simon&rsquo;s work at Stamford Bridge was under a media spotlight that was shining more intensely than on any club before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jose Mourinho was appointed Chelsea manager the same summer and colourful and highly successful times followed, with Simon busy overseeing a professional approach to dealing with the intense news interest as well as the club&rsquo;s own media output, which was growing in the digital field especially. It was during his time as head of communications that Chelsea FC launched on Facebook and Twitter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/09/02/simon_greenberg_jose_mourinho\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:75.5882%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/GT8tWaN\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To the football-watching public, Simon was most visible when sitting alongside Mourinho in charge of some of the most iconic press conferences of the Premier League and Champions League era. It was also the birth of the modern-style pre-season tour, with the squad travelling to the United States or Asia for not only warm-up matches, but also a range of other community-based activities to build interest and fanbase thousands of miles from south-west London. Simon was prominent in those.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More hidden work but with a lasting legacy was the establishment of the club&rsquo;s first corporate social responsibility programme, the forerunner to the Chelsea Foundation. That project, plus the tackling of discrimination and promotion of equality and diversity more strongly than seen before at Chelsea, are worthy tributes to Simon&rsquo;s work at the club. He left in 2009 to become chief of staff of England&rsquo;s 2018 World Cup bid before returning to the world of journalism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Simon will be sorely missed by former colleagues at the club and we send our heartfelt condolences to Simon&rsquo;s family and friends.</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:37:17','2021-09-04 06:37:17'),(18,'1630761176qNRZ23.jpeg','1630761176QNyrln.jpeg',2,'FROM ATLETICO TO CHELSEA: JIMMY FLOYD HASSELBAINK LEADS THE WAY','Saul Niguez adds to the extensive list of players to drop two thirds of the red, white and blue of Atletico Madrid to join Chelsea. We look back at a man who made that same move, for a club-record fee, 21 years ago this summer.','<h3><strong>Saul Niguez adds to the extensive list of players to drop two thirds of the red, white and blue of Atletico Madrid to join Chelsea. We look back at a man who made that same move, for a club-record fee, 21 years ago this summer.</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHad the rivalry between Chelsea and Leeds United not been quite so intense, and had Gianluca Vialli got his way, this feature would not be written.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of a 1998/99 season in which his Blues side had been a prolific goalscorer short of being crowned champions, the Blues&rsquo; Italian manager had set his sights on the man who he was convinced would fire us to glory. That player was not, however, Chris Sutton, who Vialli would soon be sat alongside in the stands at Stamford Bridge, smiling for photos and holding up a club scarf, as was customary at unveilings in those days. It was Hasselbaink, fresh off a season when he had earned a share of the Premier League Golden Boot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/theshed/shot-of-the-day/GettyImages-1221181\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:65.5882%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/wSAjy2h\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having made it clear he wanted to leave Leeds United, the most serious interest in Hasselbaink was coming from two clubs: Atletico Madrid and Chelsea. As talks between the player and his current team became increasingly fraught, the then 27-year-old issued an ultimatum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;Come on then,&rsquo; Hasselbaink recalls saying to the Leeds board, a story he relays in his autobiography Jimmy [Italics]. &lsquo;Why don&rsquo;t you negotiate with Chelsea?&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thanks to Leeds chairman Peter Ridsdale steadfastly refusing to even negotiate with Chelsea and Los Rojiblancos agreeing a fee with the Whites after the Dutchman handed in a transfer request, Hasselbaink missed out on becoming the first player since Jim McCalliog in the 1960s to have traded life at Elland Road for Stamford Bridge, instead moving to the Spanish capital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was joining a club that, despite only being three years removed from a famous league and cup Double, was on the wane. They&rsquo;d finished the previous season 13th in La Liga, although there was decent progress in the cups, as they reached the UEFA Cup semi-finals and were beaten finalists in the Copa Del Rey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/09/03/hasselbaink-atletico-2\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:76.7647%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/LOiy6OH\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hasselbaink&rsquo;s most memorable moment as an Atletico Madrid player was a two-goal display in a 3-1 victory at Real Madrid in the 1999/00 season, when he received a standing ovation from both sets of supporters after being substituted. It had been 10 years since they had won at the home of their city rivals and the wait for the next victory would be even longer &ndash; finally arriving in 2013/14, when they shocked La Liga to claim the title. This season, however, would be very different, as things swiftly went south.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the spring, with the club 17th in the standings, a tearful Ranieri resigned. Hasselbaink eventually finished with 24 La Liga goals to his name, but that proved to be half of his side&rsquo;s tally in the league, and they were relegated. Too good to go down? This was one of the more extreme examples of that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking on the Sky Sports Transfer Talk podcast two summers ago, Hasselbaink revealed he already knew his next destination before taking to the field for the club in the Copa Del Rey final, which was Atletico&rsquo;s final chance to salvage any pride from the season. He received a phone call on the way to the stadium and on the other end of the line was none other than Vialli.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;He said: &ldquo;I know you have a game, I just want you to know that we are interested. Concentrate on your game but afterwards let&#39;s talk.&rdquo;&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fit,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/09/03/atletico-hasselbaink\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:76.6177%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/Vem2CUk\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:42:56','2021-09-04 06:42:56'),(19,'1630761301gRFWpb.jpeg','1630761301YWR6eB.jpeg',3,'WOMEN’S PLAY PREDICTOR HAS ARRIVED!','Play Predictor is getting bigger and better this season with more chances to win big prizes with the launch of Chelsea Women’s Play Predictor for the 2021/22 season, exclusively on The 5th Stand app.','<h2>Play Predictor is getting bigger and better this season with more chances to win big prizes with the launch of Chelsea Women&rsquo;s Play Predictor for the 2021/22 season, exclusively on The 5th Stand app.</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>As Chelsea Women prepare to kick off the new WSL season and defend their 2020/21 title, you have the chance to become the inaugural Chelsea Women&rsquo;s Play Predictor champion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All you need to do is predict key match events each time Chelsea Women play this season. Points are on offer for predicting&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The correct score</li>\r\n	<li>Timing of Chelsea&rsquo;s first goal</li>\r\n	<li>The number of corners and more</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>If you score more points than other fans competing in the game around the world and manage to top the table, you could win big*.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every game you are in with a chance of winning a &pound;100 Megastore voucher and a Nike women&rsquo;s Chelsea shirt or football signed by the Women&rsquo;s squad, while the top scorer each month will take home a &pound;500 Megastore voucher and either a Nintendo Switch, iPad or PS5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are the highest-scoring player and are crowned Chelsea Women&rsquo;s Play Predictor champion at the end of the 2021/22 season, you will win an all-expenses-paid VIP matchday experience. Make sure you get your entries in from the first game to be in with a chance of winning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The game opens today ahead of the Blues&rsquo; Women&rsquo;s Super League clash against Arsenal at 12.30pm on Sunday (5 September), closing one hour before kick-off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t miss out on even more chances to win exclusive prizes every game this season with Women&rsquo;s Play Predictor. Download The 5th Stand app, top the table, win big!</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:45:01','2021-09-04 06:45:01'),(20,'1630761531ea79Nv.jpeg','1630761531SAhO0X.jpeg',2,'TRY OUR CESAR AZPILICUETA QUIZ!','Reckon you know all there is to know about our club captain? Then why not put five minutes aside to try our tricky little test!','<h3><strong>Reckon you know all there is to know about our club captain? Then why not put five minutes aside to try our tricky little test!</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our super Spaniard signed for Chelsea on this day in 2012 and he&#39;s proved to be one of the best bits of business we&#39;ve ever seen at Stamford Bridge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But how much do you know about Azpi&#39;s Chelsea career? We&#39;ve pulled out 10 questions on the skipper for you to try below. Go!</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:48:51','2021-09-04 06:48:51'),(21,'1630761865ugAuxJ.jpeg','1630761865RWOKad.jpeg',2,'MOUNT HIGHLIGHTS ENGLAND\'S \'CONFIDENCE\' AFTER BIG WIN IN HOSTILE ATMOSPHERE','Hungary in such a hostile atmosphere shows the confidence and strength in character within the Three Lions’ squad.','<h3><strong>Mason Mount believes England&rsquo;s win over Hungary in such a hostile atmosphere shows the confidence and strength in character within the Three Lions&rsquo; squad.</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chelsea midfielder played a key role as Gareth Southgate&rsquo;s side brushed aside Hungary in a World Cup qualifier last week, setting up Raheem Sterling for the opening goal in Budapest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The home fans were pictured throwing cups of drink at the England players as they celebrated, with the Three Lions having the last laugh as further goals from Harry Kane, Harry Maguire and Declan Rice secured a comfortable three points.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fill,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,g_auto,h_382,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/editorial/news/2021/09/03/Mount_England_GettyImages-1235016762\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:56.1765%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/QAyO4bU\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the game, Mount spoke to the media and highlighted the confidence in the England squad and how the reaction from the partisan home crowd played a part in the victory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;I don&rsquo;t think we have ever been scared of anything,&rsquo; the Chelsea midfielder explained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;We are growing in confidence, it is not over-confidence, but we know what we have got in the team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;When the whole stadium is against us we grow. As players we spoke about it and knew it would be a hostile environment and we revel in the opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div data-oembed-url=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/chelsea-production/image/upload/c_fill,dpr_auto,f_auto,fl_lossy,g_auto,h_382,q_auto,w_680,z_1.0/v1/chelsea-app/England-players-Hungary-GettyImages-1337894886\">\r\n<div style=\"max-width:816px\">\r\n<div style=\"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:56.1765%; position:relative; width:100%\"><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" src=\"//if-cdn.com/WP6aeii\" style=\"top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;\" tabindex=\"-1\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2021-09-04 06:54:25','2021-09-04 06:54:25');
